WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.437 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:03.437 --> 00:00:21.150 align:middle line:90%


00:00:21.150 --> 00:00:23.900 align:middle line:10%
As children, many of us were
drawn to stories and films

00:00:23.900 --> 00:00:27.300 align:middle line:10%
about animals who could talk
to us and be our best friends.

00:00:27.300 --> 00:00:29.300 align:middle line:10%
Some kids took it
a little further.

00:00:29.300 --> 00:00:32.670 align:middle line:84%
As a little girl, Linda Bender
rescued animals of all sorts,

00:00:32.670 --> 00:00:35.480 align:middle line:84%
and developed the ability to
understand their thoughts.

00:00:35.480 --> 00:00:38.190 align:middle line:84%
It's no surprise she chose the
field of veterinary medicine

00:00:38.190 --> 00:00:39.520 align:middle line:90%
as her profession.

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:41.880 align:middle line:84%
This has taken her to
wild animal refuges

00:00:41.880 --> 00:00:44.010 align:middle line:84%
around the world,
and into the minds

00:00:44.010 --> 00:00:46.200 align:middle line:90%
of our companion dogs and cats.

00:00:46.200 --> 00:00:49.980 align:middle line:84%
She's with us today to share her
unique perspective on the magic

00:00:49.980 --> 00:00:52.010 align:middle line:90%
of living alongside animals.

00:00:52.010 --> 00:00:52.910 align:middle line:90%
I'm so happy.

00:00:52.910 --> 00:00:55.921 align:middle line:84%
I've been dying to talk to you,
because I too love animals.

00:00:55.921 --> 00:00:56.620 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:00:56.620 --> 00:00:59.211 align:middle line:84%
And you have something
extraordinary to share with us.

00:00:59.211 --> 00:00:59.910 align:middle line:90%
Thank you.

00:00:59.910 --> 00:01:02.130 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to get into
your life as a little girl.

00:01:02.130 --> 00:01:04.631 align:middle line:84%
This has been going on
almost since you were born.

00:01:04.631 --> 00:01:05.330 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:01:05.330 --> 00:01:06.890 align:middle line:84%
But first, can I share
something with you--

00:01:06.890 --> 00:01:08.050 align:middle line:84%
Absolutely.
---that just happened?

00:01:08.050 --> 00:01:08.749 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:01:08.749 --> 00:01:10.350 align:middle line:84%
Just before I came
here to the studio,

00:01:10.350 --> 00:01:11.445 align:middle line:90%
I was talking to a woman.

00:01:11.445 --> 00:01:14.790 align:middle line:84%
And she said, so
what's your day like?

00:01:14.790 --> 00:01:16.380 align:middle line:84%
I said, oh, I'm
interviewing Linda Bender.

00:01:16.380 --> 00:01:17.350 align:middle line:90%
And she said, oh my.

00:01:17.350 --> 00:01:19.490 align:middle line:84%
I have to share
this story with you.

00:01:19.490 --> 00:01:22.570 align:middle line:84%
And she told me the
story of a horse.

00:01:22.570 --> 00:01:24.860 align:middle line:90%
She had always wanted a horse.

00:01:24.860 --> 00:01:28.050 align:middle line:84%
And what happened
was she had this--

00:01:28.050 --> 00:01:29.540 align:middle line:90%
we can see this horse here.

00:01:29.540 --> 00:01:30.750 align:middle line:90%
This course came to her.

00:01:30.750 --> 00:01:33.470 align:middle line:84%
And we won't show the
next photo for just a sec.

00:01:33.470 --> 00:01:36.910 align:middle line:84%
What happened was three years
before this horse came to her,

00:01:36.910 --> 00:01:41.230 align:middle line:84%
she wanted one so badly that
she had some glasswork done.

00:01:41.230 --> 00:01:42.880 align:middle line:90%
And she put it in her office.

00:01:42.880 --> 00:01:43.730 align:middle line:90%
It had the sun.

00:01:43.730 --> 00:01:46.120 align:middle line:84%
It had her as a
little light fairy,

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:48.190 align:middle line:84%
and her beautiful
horse underneath it,

00:01:48.190 --> 00:01:50.930 align:middle line:84%
hoping that horse would
come to her one day.

00:01:50.930 --> 00:01:52.800 align:middle line:90%
Well, the horse did come to her.

00:01:52.800 --> 00:01:56.240 align:middle line:84%
Now let's take-- and by
a very strange event.

00:01:56.240 --> 00:01:59.770 align:middle line:84%
Her boss saw this
horse in a pasture,

00:01:59.770 --> 00:02:01.440 align:middle line:90%
bought it for no reason.

00:02:01.440 --> 00:02:04.060 align:middle line:84%
This is the stained
glass she had

00:02:04.060 --> 00:02:08.844 align:middle line:84%
done three years before, which
is identical to that horse.

00:02:08.844 --> 00:02:10.110 align:middle line:84%
And when you see it
in person, you can

00:02:10.110 --> 00:02:12.290 align:middle line:90%
see the color is even better.

00:02:12.290 --> 00:02:15.520 align:middle line:84%
That horse was given to her as
a gift by her boss, who said,

00:02:15.520 --> 00:02:16.920 align:middle line:84%
I just saw this
horse and bought it.

00:02:16.920 --> 00:02:18.530 align:middle line:90%
I had no idea why.

00:02:18.530 --> 00:02:20.750 align:middle line:84%
And he said, I was going
to sell it, but hey,

00:02:20.750 --> 00:02:21.880 align:middle line:90%
do you want a horse?

00:02:21.880 --> 00:02:23.951 align:middle line:84%
Gave her this horse,
which looked identical.

00:02:23.951 --> 00:02:24.650 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE].

00:02:24.650 --> 00:02:27.470 align:middle line:84%
And the man said, that
horse seemed to speak to me.

00:02:27.470 --> 00:02:29.440 align:middle line:90%
He wanted to come to you.

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:31.270 align:middle line:84%
And that's kind of a
set-up for what we're

00:02:31.270 --> 00:02:32.250 align:middle line:90%
going to be talking about.

00:02:32.250 --> 00:02:32.950 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:02:32.950 --> 00:02:34.030 align:middle line:90%
Thank you for sharing that.

00:02:34.030 --> 00:02:34.830 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS]

00:02:34.830 --> 00:02:36.340 align:middle line:90%
I thought it was so beautiful.

00:02:36.340 --> 00:02:38.500 align:middle line:84%
She's just still
stunned to the bones

00:02:38.500 --> 00:02:41.320 align:middle line:84%
that this horse found her--
-Yes.

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:43.010 align:middle line:84%
---and had to go
through a lot of strange

00:02:43.010 --> 00:02:46.331 align:middle line:84%
people and circumstance
to find his way to her.

00:02:46.331 --> 00:02:47.030 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:02:47.030 --> 00:02:49.800 align:middle line:84%
And so let's start
now with you and how

00:02:49.800 --> 00:02:52.530 align:middle line:84%
you came to be the one that
could speak to those horses,

00:02:52.530 --> 00:02:55.010 align:middle line:84%
for example, when you
were a little girl.

00:02:55.010 --> 00:02:57.780 align:middle line:84%
Well, just let me
say the universe

00:02:57.780 --> 00:02:59.630 align:middle line:90%
does work in strange ways.

00:02:59.630 --> 00:03:01.730 align:middle line:10%
Indeed.

00:03:01.730 --> 00:03:05.510 align:middle line:10%
Many ways we have
yet to, and probably

00:03:05.510 --> 00:03:07.380 align:middle line:10%
will never, understand.

00:03:07.380 --> 00:03:11.350 align:middle line:10%
But for me, about
a year or so ago,

00:03:11.350 --> 00:03:14.520 align:middle line:10%
I was giving a lecture
on the sacred connection

00:03:14.520 --> 00:03:16.440 align:middle line:10%
between humans and animals.

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:20.170 align:middle line:84%
And a woman came up to
me afterward and asked,

00:03:20.170 --> 00:03:22.050 align:middle line:90%
I love your stories, Linda.

00:03:22.050 --> 00:03:24.030 align:middle line:84%
Tell me, when did
this connection

00:03:24.030 --> 00:03:26.140 align:middle line:90%
begin with you and the animals?

00:03:26.140 --> 00:03:29.910 align:middle line:90%
What was it like before?

00:03:29.910 --> 00:03:34.910 align:middle line:84%
And I thought for a minute,
and replied, I don't remember.

00:03:34.910 --> 00:03:38.300 align:middle line:84%
I simply could not
remember a time before.

00:03:38.300 --> 00:03:42.340 align:middle line:84%
So later that evening, and
actually the next few days,

00:03:42.340 --> 00:03:44.940 align:middle line:90%
I thought about that.

00:03:44.940 --> 00:03:50.260 align:middle line:84%
And what came to mind
finally was a time

00:03:50.260 --> 00:03:51.410 align:middle line:90%
when I was a little girl.

00:03:51.410 --> 00:03:54.750 align:middle line:90%
I'm guessing six, seven.

00:03:54.750 --> 00:03:57.380 align:middle line:84%
And I used to play
in my backyard.

00:03:57.380 --> 00:03:59.910 align:middle line:90%
It was a suburb of New Jersey.

00:03:59.910 --> 00:04:03.980 align:middle line:84%
And there were wonderful birds
and wildlife in the backyard,

00:04:03.980 --> 00:04:08.090 align:middle line:90%
in an apple orchard past that.

00:04:08.090 --> 00:04:10.780 align:middle line:84%
And I was coming back
from the orchard one day.

00:04:10.780 --> 00:04:14.990 align:middle line:84%
And as I walked, I heard
a particularly crazy crowd

00:04:14.990 --> 00:04:17.155 align:middle line:84%
of jays, and that
peculiar call they have.

00:04:17.155 --> 00:04:17.855 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:04:17.855 --> 00:04:18.670 align:middle line:90%
The call, the call.

00:04:18.670 --> 00:04:19.410 align:middle line:90%
Very aggressive.

00:04:19.410 --> 00:04:20.284 align:middle line:90%
Something's up here.

00:04:20.284 --> 00:04:20.984 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:04:20.984 --> 00:04:22.590 align:middle line:90%
Something's up here.

00:04:22.590 --> 00:04:25.760 align:middle line:84%
And I, of course,
went straight over.

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:31.270 align:middle line:84%
And there on the ground was
just a little ball of fluff.

00:04:31.270 --> 00:04:32.850 align:middle line:90%
I thought, what is that?

00:04:32.850 --> 00:04:34.870 align:middle line:90%
So I went over closer to look.

00:04:34.870 --> 00:04:39.160 align:middle line:84%
And there were about six or
seven little balls of fluff.

00:04:39.160 --> 00:04:44.470 align:middle line:84%
And upon careful inspection,
there were the most

00:04:44.470 --> 00:04:46.010 align:middle line:90%
beautiful little tiny babies.

00:04:46.010 --> 00:04:47.860 align:middle line:84%
They were nestlings
that had prematurely

00:04:47.860 --> 00:04:49.670 align:middle line:90%
fallen out of the nest.

00:04:49.670 --> 00:04:52.860 align:middle line:84%
Mom and dad, and all
the uncles and aunts,

00:04:52.860 --> 00:04:56.410 align:middle line:90%
were circling, goading me away.

00:04:56.410 --> 00:04:59.170 align:middle line:84%
But I persevered, reached
down, scooped them

00:04:59.170 --> 00:05:04.550 align:middle line:84%
up just as I was dive bombed on
the head, ran to the back door,

00:05:04.550 --> 00:05:06.170 align:middle line:90%
where my father met me.

00:05:06.170 --> 00:05:08.320 align:middle line:90%
And he gathered a box.

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:10.730 align:middle line:84%
We put these little
babies in there.

00:05:10.730 --> 00:05:14.630 align:middle line:84%
They looked up at me,
and their eyes stared,

00:05:14.630 --> 00:05:18.120 align:middle line:84%
their beaks were open, they
were screaming for life.

00:05:18.120 --> 00:05:20.670 align:middle line:84%
And I can still
remember the connection.

00:05:20.670 --> 00:05:23.320 align:middle line:90%
My eyes met their eyes.

00:05:23.320 --> 00:05:25.437 align:middle line:90%
Those tiny little eyes.

00:05:25.437 --> 00:05:26.170 align:middle line:90%
And you never stopped.

00:05:26.170 --> 00:05:28.270 align:middle line:84%
And that connection
never stopped.

00:05:28.270 --> 00:05:29.350 align:middle line:90%
Well, here we see this.

00:05:29.350 --> 00:05:30.570 align:middle line:90%
I just love this.

00:05:30.570 --> 00:05:33.140 align:middle line:90%
This was a few years later.

00:05:33.140 --> 00:05:37.600 align:middle line:84%
And I might mention
that over the years,

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:41.110 align:middle line:84%
they no longer
pecked me ever again.

00:05:41.110 --> 00:05:43.390 align:middle line:90%
They recognized me.

00:05:43.390 --> 00:05:46.110 align:middle line:84%
Generation after generation
in the corvid family,

00:05:46.110 --> 00:05:48.480 align:middle line:90%
like crows, animals recognize.

00:05:48.480 --> 00:05:50.930 align:middle line:84%
They knew me as a
helper, not a foe.

00:05:50.930 --> 00:05:52.995 align:middle line:84%
So they used to let me
do this sort of thing.

00:05:52.995 --> 00:05:53.694 align:middle line:90%
Well, look at this.

00:05:53.694 --> 00:05:56.740 align:middle line:84%
They're all sitting
on this little stick.

00:05:56.740 --> 00:05:58.660 align:middle line:84%
They're not afraid
of you at all.

00:05:58.660 --> 00:06:00.170 align:middle line:90%
And you're feeding them again.

00:06:00.170 --> 00:06:02.605 align:middle line:84%
It looks like they got the boot
or fell out of the nest early.

00:06:02.605 --> 00:06:04.291 align:middle line:84%
You're feeding them
with a little dropper.

00:06:04.291 --> 00:06:04.990 align:middle line:90%
LINDA BENDER: Right.

00:06:04.990 --> 00:06:07.320 align:middle line:84%
And this is essentially
how you spent your youth.

00:06:07.320 --> 00:06:08.310 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:06:08.310 --> 00:06:09.650 align:middle line:90%
Very much so.

00:06:09.650 --> 00:06:11.660 align:middle line:84%
Well, it was certainly
no surprise that you

00:06:11.660 --> 00:06:13.465 align:middle line:90%
were going to become a vet.

00:06:13.465 --> 00:06:14.800 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS]

00:06:14.800 --> 00:06:17.490 align:middle line:84%
So tell us about, as you
went through life, you also

00:06:17.490 --> 00:06:20.061 align:middle line:84%
must have had house
pets in your youth.

00:06:20.061 --> 00:06:20.760 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:06:20.760 --> 00:06:25.780 align:middle line:84%
And did you start connecting
with them in that way as well?

00:06:25.780 --> 00:06:26.890 align:middle line:90%
I did.

00:06:26.890 --> 00:06:32.280 align:middle line:84%
My earlier childhood
stories were mostly outside.

00:06:32.280 --> 00:06:36.990 align:middle line:84%
I had a mother who had a
dog, a young dog-- a poodle.

00:06:36.990 --> 00:06:41.680 align:middle line:84%
And I loved that little poodle,
but I always wanted a cat.

00:06:41.680 --> 00:06:46.640 align:middle line:84%
And my mom was allergic, so
I never got the cat I wanted.

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:50.300 align:middle line:84%
But it wasn't until my
20's that I actually

00:06:50.300 --> 00:06:55.340 align:middle line:84%
got my first cat, who I found
with a little Nestle's milk

00:06:55.340 --> 00:06:56.240 align:middle line:90%
can on his head.

00:06:56.240 --> 00:06:59.470 align:middle line:84%
Actually, animals
usually find me.

00:06:59.470 --> 00:07:00.590 align:middle line:84%
He had a little
can on his head?

00:07:00.590 --> 00:07:01.690 align:middle line:84%
He had a little
can on his head.

00:07:01.690 --> 00:07:02.417 align:middle line:90%
And he came--

00:07:02.417 --> 00:07:03.950 align:middle line:84%
He'd been trying to
lick it and it got stuck?

00:07:03.950 --> 00:07:05.060 align:middle line:90%
Yes, stuck on his head.

00:07:05.060 --> 00:07:07.210 align:middle line:84%
So of course I
picked him up, got

00:07:07.210 --> 00:07:10.430 align:middle line:84%
him out of that predicament,
and it was, again, instant love.

00:07:10.430 --> 00:07:12.880 align:middle line:84%
So we were together
for 20 years.

00:07:12.880 --> 00:07:14.430 align:middle line:90%
And that was my cat Whimsy.

00:07:14.430 --> 00:07:16.030 align:middle line:90%
REGINA MEREDITH: Whimsy, yes.

00:07:16.030 --> 00:07:18.461 align:middle line:84%
We're going to talk about
Whimsy in a little bit again.

00:07:18.461 --> 00:07:20.600 align:middle line:84%
LINDA BENDER: Yes.
-And, OK.

00:07:20.600 --> 00:07:25.460 align:middle line:84%
So as you graduated from
veterinarian school,

00:07:25.460 --> 00:07:28.390 align:middle line:84%
did you have a different kind
of connection with the animals

00:07:28.390 --> 00:07:30.037 align:middle line:84%
when you were going
through your training?

00:07:30.037 --> 00:07:31.070 align:middle line:90%
LINDA BENDER: Yes, and it was--

00:07:31.070 --> 00:07:32.830 align:middle line:84%
Did you see the whole
process of what you were

00:07:32.830 --> 00:07:33.860 align:middle line:90%
learning in a different way?

00:07:33.860 --> 00:07:35.550 align:middle line:90%
It was very difficult for me.

00:07:35.550 --> 00:07:37.550 align:middle line:84%
And even before vet
school, I remember

00:07:37.550 --> 00:07:42.130 align:middle line:84%
my first encounter at a
vet clinic was oh, come on.

00:07:42.130 --> 00:07:43.060 align:middle line:90%
Yes, volunteer.

00:07:43.060 --> 00:07:44.370 align:middle line:90%
Come in here.

00:07:44.370 --> 00:07:46.570 align:middle line:90%
Just help hold this dog.

00:07:46.570 --> 00:07:49.850 align:middle line:84%
And of course, I ran over, and
I was going to save and rescue

00:07:49.850 --> 00:07:52.440 align:middle line:90%
my first animal in the clinic.

00:07:52.440 --> 00:07:55.590 align:middle line:84%
And unfortunately,
it was a euthanasia.

00:07:55.590 --> 00:07:56.407 align:middle line:90%
So the dog--

00:07:56.407 --> 00:07:57.140 align:middle line:90%
REGINA MEREDITH: Whoa.

00:07:57.140 --> 00:07:59.380 align:middle line:90%
What a horrible emotional shock.

00:07:59.380 --> 00:08:01.750 align:middle line:84%
And it was a big
emotional shock,

00:08:01.750 --> 00:08:06.750 align:middle line:84%
but it was my first lesson that
this is not going to be all

00:08:06.750 --> 00:08:09.650 align:middle line:84%
rosy, and that there
is a side of veterinary

00:08:09.650 --> 00:08:13.886 align:middle line:84%
medicine that requires a
certain amount of courage--

00:08:13.886 --> 00:08:15.800 align:middle line:84%
Absolutely.
---to persevere.

00:08:15.800 --> 00:08:18.740 align:middle line:90%
And other stories, many of them.

00:08:18.740 --> 00:08:19.810 align:middle line:90%
Many others.

00:08:19.810 --> 00:08:22.750 align:middle line:84%
Well, before we go into
the veterinary clinic,

00:08:22.750 --> 00:08:24.250 align:middle line:84%
and before we
start talking about

00:08:24.250 --> 00:08:26.980 align:middle line:84%
our fuzzy little companions,
your work took you

00:08:26.980 --> 00:08:28.650 align:middle line:90%
out with large game animals.

00:08:28.650 --> 00:08:32.559 align:middle line:84%
And you had a couple of
really mystical experiences.

00:08:32.559 --> 00:08:37.990 align:middle line:84%
But let's talk about who
they are on this planet,

00:08:37.990 --> 00:08:41.740 align:middle line:84%
and what they're
looking to from us.

00:08:41.740 --> 00:08:44.151 align:middle line:84%
As you told me off camera, we're
encroaching on their territory.

00:08:44.151 --> 00:08:44.850 align:middle line:90%
LINDA BENDER: Yes.

00:08:44.850 --> 00:08:47.161 align:middle line:84%
We're damaging the
environment of the planet.

00:08:47.161 --> 00:08:48.180 align:middle line:84%
LINDA BENDER: Yes.
Yes.

00:08:48.180 --> 00:08:50.640 align:middle line:84%
They have very specific
ideas, thoughts,

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:52.607 align:middle line:84%
and feelings about all this.
-They do.

00:08:52.607 --> 00:08:54.040 align:middle line:84%
And so why don't you
just start telling us

00:08:54.040 --> 00:08:57.150 align:middle line:84%
about some of your wild
refuge experiences?

00:08:57.150 --> 00:09:00.830 align:middle line:84%
Well, I've had quite a
bit of that experience.

00:09:00.830 --> 00:09:05.880 align:middle line:84%
And back in the day, I was
living in Southeast Asia.

00:09:05.880 --> 00:09:09.100 align:middle line:84%
And I did a lot of
work with animals

00:09:09.100 --> 00:09:12.200 align:middle line:84%
who were victims of
the animal trafficking

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:15.040 align:middle line:84%
trade. i tried to rehabilitate
them, keep them alive.

00:09:15.040 --> 00:09:16.380 align:middle line:90%
Rehabilitate them.

00:09:16.380 --> 00:09:21.760 align:middle line:84%
And so I was able to see all
kinds of amazing animals.

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:32.310 align:middle line:84%
Tigers, leopards, gorillas,
rare, rare psittacine parrots.

00:09:32.310 --> 00:09:36.970 align:middle line:84%
And the problem
that I encountered

00:09:36.970 --> 00:09:42.150 align:middle line:84%
was the ability
to continue doing

00:09:42.150 --> 00:09:45.180 align:middle line:84%
my work knowing that
there was such cruelty

00:09:45.180 --> 00:09:48.940 align:middle line:90%
and ignorance in the world.

00:09:48.940 --> 00:09:50.630 align:middle line:90%
It was difficult time.

00:09:50.630 --> 00:09:55.080 align:middle line:84%
I almost gave up one or
two times-- probably more

00:09:55.080 --> 00:09:56.530 align:middle line:90%
than one or two times.

00:09:56.530 --> 00:09:59.860 align:middle line:84%
But my connection and my
conviction to the animals

00:09:59.860 --> 00:10:03.600 align:middle line:84%
became deeper and deeper
through this process.

00:10:03.600 --> 00:10:08.640 align:middle line:84%
And, you know, we are now 7
billion people on the planet.

00:10:08.640 --> 00:10:14.150 align:middle line:84%
And so for reasons
of loss of habitat,

00:10:14.150 --> 00:10:21.330 align:middle line:84%
pollution, and hunting,
we're losing so many of our--

00:10:21.330 --> 00:10:22.030 align:middle line:90%
REGINA MEREDITH: Yes.

00:10:22.030 --> 00:10:26.050 align:middle line:84%
---our animals, especially
the large land mammals.

00:10:26.050 --> 00:10:28.640 align:middle line:84%
The elephants that
are meant to be

00:10:28.640 --> 00:10:33.810 align:middle line:84%
walking the longitudinal
meridians in Africa

00:10:33.810 --> 00:10:35.520 align:middle line:90%
are now being cut off.

00:10:35.520 --> 00:10:38.800 align:middle line:90%
They can't do that anymore.

00:10:38.800 --> 00:10:41.750 align:middle line:84%
A small example of
how that severely

00:10:41.750 --> 00:10:46.070 align:middle line:84%
affects all animals-- it isn't
only that the elephants suffer.

00:10:46.070 --> 00:10:49.550 align:middle line:84%
One enormous footprint
of an elephant

00:10:49.550 --> 00:10:53.895 align:middle line:84%
creates an entire ecosystem
for other small species.

00:10:53.895 --> 00:10:58.340 align:middle line:84%
And in the rain, when the rains
dry, and in the dry periods,

00:10:58.340 --> 00:11:02.770 align:middle line:84%
that creates an entire water
well for other small birds,

00:11:02.770 --> 00:11:04.180 align:middle line:90%
other creatures.

00:11:04.180 --> 00:11:07.650 align:middle line:90%
So that's one example.

00:11:07.650 --> 00:11:09.199 align:middle line:84%
There's so many.
-Yes.

00:11:09.199 --> 00:11:12.500 align:middle line:84%
And tell us about
another, maybe a couple

00:11:12.500 --> 00:11:17.960 align:middle line:84%
of your kind of heart-to-heart,
soul-to-soul experiences

00:11:17.960 --> 00:11:20.820 align:middle line:84%
you had with some of
these wild animals.

00:11:20.820 --> 00:11:22.670 align:middle line:84%
I would love to
hear some of that,

00:11:22.670 --> 00:11:25.240 align:middle line:84%
and what they were
trying to convey to you.

00:11:25.240 --> 00:11:32.280 align:middle line:84%
Well, what I believe
is happening in wildlife

00:11:32.280 --> 00:11:36.540 align:middle line:84%
is that because we
are so many humans,

00:11:36.540 --> 00:11:41.260 align:middle line:84%
they no longer live in
blissful ignorance of us.

00:11:41.260 --> 00:11:45.400 align:middle line:84%
They are now being forced
to connect with us in ways

00:11:45.400 --> 00:11:47.740 align:middle line:90%
that they've never done before.

00:11:47.740 --> 00:11:53.850 align:middle line:84%
So to those people
who are interested,

00:11:53.850 --> 00:11:58.640 align:middle line:84%
who open from their
hearts, I would describe it

00:11:58.640 --> 00:12:02.630 align:middle line:84%
as if animals-- all
animals, companion

00:12:02.630 --> 00:12:09.860 align:middle line:84%
animals and wildlife-- offer
us an invitation to connect.

00:12:09.860 --> 00:12:17.310 align:middle line:84%
And if we choose to look at
that invitation and respond,

00:12:17.310 --> 00:12:22.040 align:middle line:84%
they are then willing to
come to us at whatever level

00:12:22.040 --> 00:12:28.230 align:middle line:84%
we are able to understand,
and help share their concerns,

00:12:28.230 --> 00:12:31.080 align:middle line:84%
and their lives,
and their cultures.

00:12:31.080 --> 00:12:34.310 align:middle line:90%
For me, all life is soul.

00:12:34.310 --> 00:12:37.725 align:middle line:84%
All life is connected, as
we're learning now in physics,

00:12:37.725 --> 00:12:39.500 align:middle line:90%
in quantum physics.

00:12:39.500 --> 00:12:41.810 align:middle line:84%
My son is an
aspiring physicists,

00:12:41.810 --> 00:12:44.020 align:middle line:84%
so I always confirm
these things with him.

00:12:44.020 --> 00:12:45.419 align:middle line:84%
Yes.
Yes.

00:12:45.419 --> 00:12:46.230 align:middle line:90%
And I got the nod.

00:12:46.230 --> 00:12:46.930 align:middle line:90%
Yes, mom.

00:12:46.930 --> 00:12:49.090 align:middle line:90%
We are all connected.

00:12:49.090 --> 00:12:52.300 align:middle line:84%
But it is, to me,
wonderful confirmation

00:12:52.300 --> 00:13:00.100 align:middle line:84%
of what I understood as a
child-- which does remind me

00:13:00.100 --> 00:13:03.070 align:middle line:84%
of a time when I was
a child and I was

00:13:03.070 --> 00:13:05.800 align:middle line:90%
looking out my bedroom window.

00:13:05.800 --> 00:13:09.265 align:middle line:84%
And there was a beautiful
robin in a branch.

00:13:09.265 --> 00:13:13.950 align:middle line:84%
And I just enjoyed listening
to that robin sing,

00:13:13.950 --> 00:13:16.430 align:middle line:90%
and admiring its beautiful nest.

00:13:16.430 --> 00:13:19.751 align:middle line:84%
Robins are just
awesome nest builders.

00:13:19.751 --> 00:13:20.450 align:middle line:90%
They're the best.

00:13:20.450 --> 00:13:22.311 align:middle line:84%
They're so precise in
their nest building.

00:13:22.311 --> 00:13:24.930 align:middle line:84%
-They're the best.
-Yes, they're experts.

00:13:24.930 --> 00:13:28.750 align:middle line:84%
As a matter of
fact, a female robin

00:13:28.750 --> 00:13:32.690 align:middle line:84%
will choose her mate by what
he brings to her to offer

00:13:32.690 --> 00:13:34.160 align:middle line:90%
his nest building capabilities.

00:13:34.160 --> 00:13:36.090 align:middle line:84%
REGINA MEREDITH:
Oh, interesting.

00:13:36.090 --> 00:13:36.970 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, the sticks.

00:13:36.970 --> 00:13:39.752 align:middle line:84%
And if she doesn't like the
sticks, he's out of there.

00:13:39.752 --> 00:13:40.451 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:13:40.451 --> 00:13:44.010 align:middle line:84%
But anyway, I was watching
this particular robin.

00:13:44.010 --> 00:13:47.990 align:middle line:84%
And of course, as a child,
I knew none of this,

00:13:47.990 --> 00:13:50.120 align:middle line:84%
but I believe to
this day that it

00:13:50.120 --> 00:13:55.960 align:middle line:84%
was a type of oneness experience
that I had with this robin.

00:13:55.960 --> 00:14:00.030 align:middle line:84%
Again, there was an invitation
to join, to come closer,

00:14:00.030 --> 00:14:02.750 align:middle line:90%
to connect through our hearts.

00:14:02.750 --> 00:14:06.230 align:middle line:84%
And that invitation opened
to a deeper soul connection--

00:14:06.230 --> 00:14:10.640 align:middle line:84%
to the recognition that
this is a soul, I am a soul,

00:14:10.640 --> 00:14:11.900 align:middle line:90%
but we are really one.

00:14:11.900 --> 00:14:17.060 align:middle line:84%
And we are joyously together
in this cosmic oneness.

00:14:17.060 --> 00:14:22.180 align:middle line:84%
And I remember-- I actually
remember feeling connected.

00:14:22.180 --> 00:14:25.340 align:middle line:84%
Feeling what the
vedics, the sages,

00:14:25.340 --> 00:14:31.185 align:middle line:84%
describe as loss of where my
body ends and the trees begin,

00:14:31.185 --> 00:14:35.730 align:middle line:84%
or where the body of the
bird began and ended.

00:14:35.730 --> 00:14:37.960 align:middle line:84%
And it was a
beautiful experience.

00:14:37.960 --> 00:14:43.380 align:middle line:84%
And it just happened naturally
through the connection

00:14:43.380 --> 00:14:45.220 align:middle line:90%
of a heart and soul.

00:14:45.220 --> 00:14:47.230 align:middle line:84%
So it's continued
through the wildlife,

00:14:47.230 --> 00:14:48.820 align:middle line:90%
and it continues today.

00:14:48.820 --> 00:14:50.660 align:middle line:84%
What are some of
the wildlife cultures

00:14:50.660 --> 00:14:53.530 align:middle line:84%
that you have a particular
fascination with

00:14:53.530 --> 00:14:56.820 align:middle line:90%
or respect for as cultures go?

00:14:56.820 --> 00:14:58.270 align:middle line:90%
Oh gosh, so many.

00:14:58.270 --> 00:15:01.550 align:middle line:84%
Well, all we have to do
is look out our window

00:15:01.550 --> 00:15:03.150 align:middle line:90%
to the common squirrel.

00:15:03.150 --> 00:15:04.790 align:middle line:90%
Oh, yes.

00:15:04.790 --> 00:15:05.534 align:middle line:90%
I love squirrels.

00:15:05.534 --> 00:15:06.400 align:middle line:90%
I used to hand feed them.

00:15:06.400 --> 00:15:07.980 align:middle line:90%
I do too.

00:15:07.980 --> 00:15:11.560 align:middle line:84%
Squirrels are-- you know some
people consider them pets.

00:15:11.560 --> 00:15:14.030 align:middle line:90%
They are absolutely fabulous.

00:15:14.030 --> 00:15:15.965 align:middle line:90%
They live life on the edge--

00:15:15.965 --> 00:15:16.965 align:middle line:90%
REGINA MEREDITH: Yes, they do.

00:15:16.965 --> 00:15:21.940 align:middle line:84%
---because they are,
as opposed to robins,

00:15:21.940 --> 00:15:24.200 align:middle line:84%
who are meticulous
nest builders, they are

00:15:24.200 --> 00:15:26.350 align:middle line:90%
fancy free about their nests.

00:15:26.350 --> 00:15:29.590 align:middle line:84%
You know, if something
goes wrong and whatever,

00:15:29.590 --> 00:15:32.750 align:middle line:84%
they abandon their home
and create another one.

00:15:32.750 --> 00:15:37.900 align:middle line:84%
But they also can fall great
distances and not get hurt.

00:15:37.900 --> 00:15:40.540 align:middle line:84%
Their tails are a
type of parachute.

00:15:40.540 --> 00:15:45.120 align:middle line:84%
So they become ever more daring,
I think, in their escapades.

00:15:45.120 --> 00:15:49.385 align:middle line:84%
So although it's devastating
when a squirrel runs out

00:15:49.385 --> 00:15:52.850 align:middle line:84%
in the road and
gets hurt or killed,

00:15:52.850 --> 00:15:55.350 align:middle line:84%
you know, that's
what squirrels do.

00:15:55.350 --> 00:15:59.250 align:middle line:84%
And so it's our job to
drive a little more slowly.

00:15:59.250 --> 00:16:00.730 align:middle line:90%
But I adore squirrels.

00:16:00.730 --> 00:16:02.740 align:middle line:84%
So they really
bring to the table

00:16:02.740 --> 00:16:06.491 align:middle line:84%
a sense of adventure
and wild daring.

00:16:06.491 --> 00:16:07.880 align:middle line:84%
Wildness.
Steering.

00:16:07.880 --> 00:16:09.120 align:middle line:84%
REGINA MEREDITH: Yes.
-Yes.

00:16:09.120 --> 00:16:10.546 align:middle line:84%
Yes.
-[INAUDIBLE].

00:16:10.546 --> 00:16:12.970 align:middle line:84%
And can you imagine
what you would be

00:16:12.970 --> 00:16:15.180 align:middle line:90%
like if you could jump 50 feet?

00:16:15.180 --> 00:16:16.220 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, no kidding.

00:16:16.220 --> 00:16:17.130 align:middle line:90%
You just want to do it.

00:16:17.130 --> 00:16:18.736 align:middle line:84%
You'd have to.
-Yeah.

00:16:18.736 --> 00:16:20.000 align:middle line:84%
So that's one
interesting account.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:20.580 align:middle line:84%
That's interesting.
LINDA BENDER: Yes.

00:16:20.580 --> 00:16:21.710 align:middle line:90%
What about rabbits?

00:16:21.710 --> 00:16:25.280 align:middle line:84%
I mean, everyone says,
what are they thinking?

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:26.600 align:middle line:90%
Same as with squirrels.

00:16:26.600 --> 00:16:27.620 align:middle line:90%
What are they thinking?

00:16:27.620 --> 00:16:30.390 align:middle line:84%
Why do they wait until the
car's right there to dart

00:16:30.390 --> 00:16:31.880 align:middle line:84%
right out in front of you?
LINDA BENDER: Right.

00:16:31.880 --> 00:16:33.060 align:middle line:84%
Yeah.
-What's up with that?

00:16:33.060 --> 00:16:36.910 align:middle line:84%
Well, one thing that I
feel very strongly about,

00:16:36.910 --> 00:16:42.040 align:middle line:84%
and we do need to remember,
is that animals are living

00:16:42.040 --> 00:16:43.500 align:middle line:84%
in their natural habitat.
REGINA MEREDITH: That's right.

00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:44.560 align:middle line:90%
And we're driving through it.

00:16:44.560 --> 00:16:49.690 align:middle line:84%
Be they rabbits, squirrels,
deer, whatever, they are simply

00:16:49.690 --> 00:16:51.670 align:middle line:84%
living in their habitats.
REGINA MEREDITH: Yes.

00:16:51.670 --> 00:16:54.350 align:middle line:84%
We have cut our roads
through their habitats.

00:16:54.350 --> 00:16:55.170 align:middle line:90%
REGINA MEREDITH: Yes.

00:16:55.170 --> 00:16:58.510 align:middle line:84%
So rather than thinking we
have the right of way, actually,

00:16:58.510 --> 00:16:59.340 align:middle line:90%
they do.

00:16:59.340 --> 00:17:00.073 align:middle line:90%
REGINA MEREDITH: Sure.

00:17:00.073 --> 00:17:05.010 align:middle line:84%
So all creatures
are not expecting

00:17:05.010 --> 00:17:08.639 align:middle line:90%
us to put ourselves first.

00:17:08.639 --> 00:17:10.330 align:middle line:84%
You know, I can
understand that.

00:17:10.330 --> 00:17:11.030 align:middle line:90%
LINDA BENDER: Yes.

00:17:11.030 --> 00:17:16.069 align:middle line:84%
But if the car is moving along,
why choose that really daring

00:17:16.069 --> 00:17:18.294 align:middle line:90%
moment to go, in a sense?

00:17:18.294 --> 00:17:20.950 align:middle line:84%
You know, I'd never--
you'd think if there's

00:17:20.950 --> 00:17:24.490 align:middle line:84%
an instinct for survival,
if you see a vehicle moving

00:17:24.490 --> 00:17:27.200 align:middle line:84%
towards you, there would be a
freeze or something, instead

00:17:27.200 --> 00:17:28.830 align:middle line:84%
of, oh, right, green light.
Let's go.

00:17:28.830 --> 00:17:32.360 align:middle line:84%
Well, in some
species, they don't see

00:17:32.360 --> 00:17:33.867 align:middle line:90%
particularly well, you know?

00:17:33.867 --> 00:17:35.300 align:middle line:84%
REGINA MEREDITH: Yeah,
that's a good point.

00:17:35.300 --> 00:17:37.297 align:middle line:84%
And certain species
are better at vision.

00:17:37.297 --> 00:17:38.030 align:middle line:90%
REGINA MEREDITH: Yeah.

00:17:38.030 --> 00:17:39.740 align:middle line:90%
Others are better at sound.

00:17:39.740 --> 00:17:41.200 align:middle line:90%
Others are, you know--

00:17:41.200 --> 00:17:43.361 align:middle line:84%
Well, you would think with
rabbits, it must be sound.

00:17:43.361 --> 00:17:44.060 align:middle line:90%
LINDA BENDER: Well--

00:17:44.060 --> 00:17:45.240 align:middle line:84%
But how do they
see [INAUDIBLE]?

00:17:45.240 --> 00:17:48.120 align:middle line:84%
I actually cannot
speak on behalf of--

00:17:48.120 --> 00:17:48.960 align:middle line:90%
Of rabbits.

00:17:48.960 --> 00:17:50.943 align:middle line:84%
---why that rabbit
would jump out.

00:17:50.943 --> 00:17:51.930 align:middle line:90%
Yes, I know.

00:17:51.930 --> 00:17:54.000 align:middle line:84%
It's just a common
phenomena everybody

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:54.940 align:middle line:90%
scratches their head over.

00:17:54.940 --> 00:17:55.890 align:middle line:84%
-Well, it is.
-Sure.

00:17:55.890 --> 00:17:56.590 align:middle line:90%
It is.

00:17:56.590 --> 00:17:57.871 align:middle line:84%
And maybe they
don't see that well.

00:17:57.871 --> 00:17:58.570 align:middle line:90%
You're right.

00:17:58.570 --> 00:18:01.130 align:middle line:84%
Maybe they feel the
rumbling on the ground,

00:18:01.130 --> 00:18:03.700 align:middle line:84%
and it excites them to movement
or something like that.

00:18:03.700 --> 00:18:05.530 align:middle line:84%
So maybe we could
get feedback on that.

00:18:05.530 --> 00:18:07.580 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, maybe we could
connect with them

00:18:07.580 --> 00:18:09.440 align:middle line:84%
and find out what's up.
LINDA BENDER: Yeah.

00:18:09.440 --> 00:18:14.840 align:middle line:84%
Now, you also worked with some
villagers around the world,

00:18:14.840 --> 00:18:16.430 align:middle line:90%
having to do with anti-poaching.

00:18:16.430 --> 00:18:20.141 align:middle line:84%
And this is a real-- this is a
very sensitive and very painful

00:18:20.141 --> 00:18:20.840 align:middle line:90%
kind of issue.

00:18:20.840 --> 00:18:23.641 align:middle line:84%
And can you talk to us a
little bit about what goes on--

00:18:23.641 --> 00:18:24.340 align:middle line:90%
Oh yes.

00:18:24.340 --> 00:18:26.980 align:middle line:84%
---and how we might
be, even inadvertently,

00:18:26.980 --> 00:18:32.180 align:middle line:84%
participating in it or
supporting it, if not directly?

00:18:32.180 --> 00:18:35.080 align:middle line:84%
Yes, it is
difficult. And when I

00:18:35.080 --> 00:18:38.900 align:middle line:84%
think of Africa and the
problems you speak of,

00:18:38.900 --> 00:18:40.460 align:middle line:90%
I tend to take a deep breath.

00:18:40.460 --> 00:18:43.240 align:middle line:90%
And it can be overwhelming.

00:18:43.240 --> 00:18:49.170 align:middle line:84%
But my deep philosophy in all
this is the old story of you

00:18:49.170 --> 00:18:53.390 align:middle line:84%
cannot save everything,
but you can certainly save

00:18:53.390 --> 00:18:55.670 align:middle line:90%
what walks across your path.

00:18:55.670 --> 00:18:56.790 align:middle line:90%
That is my mantra.

00:18:56.790 --> 00:18:58.520 align:middle line:90%
That is what I do.

00:18:58.520 --> 00:18:59.690 align:middle line:90%
And--

00:18:59.690 --> 00:19:03.160 align:middle line:84%
Tell us the nature, in
this day and age, of what

00:19:03.160 --> 00:19:05.220 align:middle line:90%
the poaching world is like.

00:19:05.220 --> 00:19:07.060 align:middle line:84%
I mean, because
we're sitting safely

00:19:07.060 --> 00:19:08.659 align:middle line:84%
tucked away from all of it.
LINDA BENDER: Right.

00:19:08.659 --> 00:19:09.830 align:middle line:90%
What is still being poached?

00:19:09.830 --> 00:19:11.560 align:middle line:84%
What is being taken
to extinction?

00:19:11.560 --> 00:19:13.630 align:middle line:84%
LINDA BENDER: Well,
one thing Americans

00:19:13.630 --> 00:19:17.800 align:middle line:84%
need to remember is that
although we're not--

00:19:17.800 --> 00:19:23.370 align:middle line:84%
we tend to feel just
distracted from it because,

00:19:23.370 --> 00:19:25.060 align:middle line:90%
oh, well, it isn't our problem.

00:19:25.060 --> 00:19:26.300 align:middle line:90%
We're not poaching.

00:19:26.300 --> 00:19:29.030 align:middle line:84%
But still-- it's
hard to believe,

00:19:29.030 --> 00:19:31.130 align:middle line:84%
but still, this country
is one of the biggest

00:19:31.130 --> 00:19:33.610 align:middle line:90%
markets for poached goods.

00:19:33.610 --> 00:19:36.650 align:middle line:84%
What kind of poached
goods are we talking about?

00:19:36.650 --> 00:19:41.030 align:middle line:84%
Open the pages of your
latest fashion magazines.

00:19:41.030 --> 00:19:42.210 align:middle line:84%
REGINA MEREDITH:
Well, certainly.

00:19:42.210 --> 00:19:43.730 align:middle line:90%
Flip through the pages.

00:19:43.730 --> 00:19:47.310 align:middle line:84%
You'll see that
I'm talking about.

00:19:47.310 --> 00:19:48.800 align:middle line:90%
And what about big game?

00:19:48.800 --> 00:19:51.870 align:middle line:84%
I mean, is that scene
still going on, or--

00:19:51.870 --> 00:19:54.460 align:middle line:90%
It's better.

00:19:54.460 --> 00:19:55.710 align:middle line:90%
It's not good.

00:19:55.710 --> 00:19:59.770 align:middle line:84%
But poaching in Africa, for
example, one thing we really

00:19:59.770 --> 00:20:07.360 align:middle line:84%
need to be mindful of is that
elephants, their body parts

00:20:07.360 --> 00:20:14.200 align:middle line:90%
are still being taken for ivory.

00:20:14.200 --> 00:20:17.250 align:middle line:84%
And rhinos--
actually, the poaching

00:20:17.250 --> 00:20:20.580 align:middle line:84%
of elephants and rhinos
is more now than ever.

00:20:20.580 --> 00:20:23.300 align:middle line:84%
And it's become
more sophisticated.

00:20:23.300 --> 00:20:25.220 align:middle line:84%
Poaching of--
-How so?

00:20:25.220 --> 00:20:29.860 align:middle line:84%
---those animals is probably
second only to the drug

00:20:29.860 --> 00:20:32.430 align:middle line:84%
culture in the world.
-Seriously?

00:20:32.430 --> 00:20:33.924 align:middle line:84%
It's that bad?
-Yes.

00:20:33.924 --> 00:20:40.190 align:middle line:84%
And in Asia, there's still
the old mistaken belief

00:20:40.190 --> 00:20:43.360 align:middle line:84%
that there are medicinal
qualities to those body parts.

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:44.825 align:middle line:84%
REGINA MEREDITH: Right.
Right.

00:20:44.825 --> 00:20:45.640 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:20:45.640 --> 00:20:48.380 align:middle line:84%
So education,
education, education.

00:20:48.380 --> 00:20:49.420 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

00:20:49.420 --> 00:20:52.510 align:middle line:84%
And you have spent time-- we
touched on it a moment ago.

00:20:52.510 --> 00:20:53.640 align:middle line:84%
You've spent time
with elephants.

00:20:53.640 --> 00:20:54.340 align:middle line:90%
LINDA BENDER: Yes.

00:20:54.340 --> 00:20:55.590 align:middle line:90%
I adore elephants.

00:20:55.590 --> 00:20:58.190 align:middle line:84%
Can you tell us a little
bit about their culture

00:20:58.190 --> 00:21:01.260 align:middle line:84%
and their world in India
and Southeast Asia, what

00:21:01.260 --> 00:21:03.080 align:middle line:84%
the greatest
threats to them are,

00:21:03.080 --> 00:21:05.180 align:middle line:84%
and some of the beauty
of that culture?

00:21:05.180 --> 00:21:06.700 align:middle line:90%
Oh, elephants.

00:21:06.700 --> 00:21:07.740 align:middle line:90%
I do dearly love elephants.

00:21:07.740 --> 00:21:10.120 align:middle line:84%
REGINA MEREDITH: And
you've been with elephants.

00:21:10.120 --> 00:21:11.590 align:middle line:84%
LINDA BENDER: I've
been with elephants.

00:21:11.590 --> 00:21:17.420 align:middle line:84%
I have had a few very deep
connections with elephants.

00:21:17.420 --> 00:21:21.160 align:middle line:84%
And the number one
problem with poaching--

00:21:21.160 --> 00:21:23.640 align:middle line:84%
and again, they're
always the same issues.

00:21:23.640 --> 00:21:26.830 align:middle line:84%
It's loss of habitat,
because of humans

00:21:26.830 --> 00:21:29.000 align:middle line:90%
encroaching on that territory.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:32.750 align:middle line:84%
And then there's the
farming of the humans.

00:21:32.750 --> 00:21:36.890 align:middle line:84%
So the elephants have fewer
and fewer places to go.

00:21:36.890 --> 00:21:38.290 align:middle line:90%
And they must roam.

00:21:38.290 --> 00:21:39.980 align:middle line:90%
They cannot be enclosed.

00:21:39.980 --> 00:21:42.500 align:middle line:84%
There are people
like Peter Beard,

00:21:42.500 --> 00:21:48.680 align:middle line:84%
for example, who, for many,
many years, was living in Africa

00:21:48.680 --> 00:21:52.710 align:middle line:84%
and documented the-- it's
a fascinating story, how

00:21:52.710 --> 00:21:56.210 align:middle line:84%
the first white people
came to East Africa.

00:21:56.210 --> 00:21:58.950 align:middle line:84%
And how that the
populations of wildlife

00:21:58.950 --> 00:22:03.280 align:middle line:84%
was just so vast that no
one could ever even imagine

00:22:03.280 --> 00:22:07.270 align:middle line:84%
there would ever be a
reduction in the abundance

00:22:07.270 --> 00:22:08.900 align:middle line:90%
of all wildlife.

00:22:08.900 --> 00:22:11.230 align:middle line:84%
And then some of
those early hunters

00:22:11.230 --> 00:22:15.380 align:middle line:84%
back in the time of
Roosevelt and those people,

00:22:15.380 --> 00:22:17.930 align:middle line:90%
they actually saw a decline.

00:22:17.930 --> 00:22:23.240 align:middle line:84%
And they became the first people
to set up game parks to protect

00:22:23.240 --> 00:22:25.110 align:middle line:90%
the animals and the elephants.

00:22:25.110 --> 00:22:26.980 align:middle line:84%
And they learned over
the years what worked

00:22:26.980 --> 00:22:27.940 align:middle line:90%
and what didn't work.

00:22:27.940 --> 00:22:30.230 align:middle line:84%
And what they for certain
learned is you cannot

00:22:30.230 --> 00:22:32.800 align:middle line:90%
enclose these wild beings.

00:22:32.800 --> 00:22:36.700 align:middle line:90%
And elephants need to roam.

00:22:36.700 --> 00:22:39.480 align:middle line:84%
Elephants need to
walk those meridians.

00:22:39.480 --> 00:22:42.160 align:middle line:84%
Tell us about that walking
of the longitudinal meridians

00:22:42.160 --> 00:22:44.090 align:middle line:84%
you spoke of earlier.
-Right.

00:22:44.090 --> 00:22:47.720 align:middle line:84%
That is the sacred
meridians, as well

00:22:47.720 --> 00:22:50.410 align:middle line:84%
as-- I think we're
going to hopefully

00:22:50.410 --> 00:22:52.094 align:middle line:90%
talk later about the lions--

00:22:52.094 --> 00:22:53.360 align:middle line:84%
REGINA MEREDITH:
Yes, we are going to.

00:22:53.360 --> 00:22:55.530 align:middle line:90%
---in South Africa.

00:22:55.530 --> 00:22:59.020 align:middle line:84%
The shaman, the African
shaman, the Zulu people,

00:22:59.020 --> 00:23:02.780 align:middle line:84%
and all the indigenous
cultures speak of these animals

00:23:02.780 --> 00:23:08.870 align:middle line:84%
as sacred beings who are the
first beings of the land,

00:23:08.870 --> 00:23:10.620 align:middle line:90%
and must be respected.

00:23:10.620 --> 00:23:11.320 align:middle line:90%
REGINA MEREDITH: Yes.

00:23:11.320 --> 00:23:14.417 align:middle line:84%
Unfortunately, that's
now coming into conflict.

00:23:14.417 --> 00:23:15.350 align:middle line:90%
REGINA MEREDITH: Yes, it is.

00:23:15.350 --> 00:23:18.150 align:middle line:84%
And elephants and all
the other wild creatures

00:23:18.150 --> 00:23:24.780 align:middle line:84%
are trying to learn
about us, trying to,

00:23:24.780 --> 00:23:27.510 align:middle line:90%
if possible, understand.

00:23:27.510 --> 00:23:31.800 align:middle line:84%
And they see the suffering
that we go through,

00:23:31.800 --> 00:23:35.930 align:middle line:84%
because the suffering
we inflict on them,

00:23:35.930 --> 00:23:39.074 align:middle line:84%
they also see happening
in our cultures.

00:23:39.074 --> 00:23:40.620 align:middle line:84%
-Yes.
-You know?

00:23:40.620 --> 00:23:42.521 align:middle line:84%
And you know the
great Credo Mutwa.

00:23:42.521 --> 00:23:43.670 align:middle line:84%
LINDA BENDER: I do.
Yes.

00:23:43.670 --> 00:23:45.010 align:middle line:84%
REGINA MEREDITH: And
